  "5-38": (
    caption: [Depurination and deamination are the most frequent spontaneous chemical reactions known to create serious DNA damage in cells. (A) Depurination can remove guanine (or adenine) from DNA. (B) The major type of deamination reaction converts cytosine to uracil, which, as we have seen, is not normally found in DNA. However, deamination can occur on other bases as well. Both depurination and deamination take place on double-helical DNA, and neither reaction breaks the phosphodiester backbone. H N H2O H N H H N N H O N H N H N H O N N N],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
